  "nursesNote": "After a suicide attempt the patient's risk stays high, since a prior attempt is one of the strongest predictors of future suicide. The nurse maintains close or one-to-one observation, never leaves the patient alone, and keeps the environment free of dangerous items. The approach is calm and nonjudgmental, without anger or shame, and the nurse does not minimize the attempt as merely 'a cry for help.' The nurse directly assesses current suicidal ideation, plan, and intent, and stays alert for a sudden, unexplained calm, which can signal that a decision to act has been made. Care addresses the underlying problem (such as depression or substance use) with medication and therapy, involves family and support, and builds a safety plan with follow-up. No-harm contracts are not reliable safeguards and do not replace observation and a safe environment.",
